# Windows CMD — translation cheatsheet

The OEF default shell is POSIX (`bash`/`zsh`) — see `os-shell.mdc`. Most Windows contributors run inside **WSL2**, where POSIX commands work as-is. A minority work in **native Windows CMD (`cmd.exe`)**. This rule exists for them.

> If you're in PowerShell, this rule doesn't apply — translate POSIX → PowerShell on demand instead. Don't reach for CMD syntax just because the OS is Windows.

## When to apply this rule

- The contributor explicitly says they're in CMD.
- The terminal banner / prompt indicates `cmd.exe`.
- The user pastes a CMD-style error (e.g. `'<cmd>' is not recognized as an internal or external command`).

If none of those signals are present, default to POSIX (`os-shell.mdc`) — even on Windows.

## 1) Shell and execution

- Assume commands are pasted into **cmd.exe** in Cursor's integrated terminal.
- Do **not** mix PowerShell syntax (no `Get-ChildItem`, no `$env:`, no `Remove-Item`, no `Set-Location`).
- If a doc snippet defaults to PowerShell, translate to CMD before running.

## 2) Never use Linux/macOS-only commands

Do not use: `ls`, `cat`, `grep`, `sed`, `awk`, `find` (POSIX), `pwd`, `rm -rf`, `cp`, `mv`, `touch`, `export`, `chmod`, `chown`, `./script.sh`, `curl | bash`.

## 3) CMD equivalents

| POSIX | CMD |
|-------|-----|
| `ls` | `dir` |
| `cd path` | `cd path` (relative: `cd .\folder`) |
| `pwd` | `cd` |
| `cat file.txt` | `type file.txt` |
| `grep -in "pat" file` | `findstr /n /i "pat" file` (`/s` to recurse) |
| `touch file.txt` | `type nul > file.txt` |
| `echo line >> file` | `echo line>> file` |
| `cp src dst` | `copy src dst` (folders: `xcopy /e /i src dst`) |
| `mv src dst` | `move src dst` or `ren old new` |
| `rm file` | `del /q file` |
| `rm -rf dir` | `rmdir /s /q dir` |
| `export NAME=val` (session) | `set NAME=value` |
| `export NAME=val` (persistent) | `setx NAME "value"` (applies to new terminals) |
| `./tool` | `.\tool.exe` or `.\script.bat` |
| `bash script.sh` | `call script.bat` |

## 4) Paths and quoting

- Use Windows paths with backslashes: `.\path\to\file` or `C:\path\to\file`.
- Quote paths with spaces: `"C:\Program Files\..."`.
- All filesystem paths are relative to the current workspace root.
- Never resolve paths from OS root (e.g. raw `C:\`).

## 5) Command chaining

- Chain on success: `command1 && command2`.
- Chain always: `command1 & command2`.
- Multi-line blocks use parentheses: `(command1 && command2 && command3)`.
- Use `^` for line continuation when needed.

## 6) Python / venv in CMD

```bat
python -m venv .venv
.\.venv\Scripts\activate.bat
pip install -r .\requirements.txt
pytest
python -m package.module
```

## 7) Git in CMD

```bat
git status
git checkout -b feature\my-branch
git add .
git commit -m "message"
```

## 8) Output requirements

After running commands:

- Print the exact CMD command you ran.
- Paste the relevant terminal output or error.
- Propose the next CMD-valid step.

## 9) If uncertain

If a command might be PowerShell-only, rewrite it in CMD or provide a CMD-safe alternative. Never silently default to PowerShell from this rule.
